Data Visualization I

CODE 1 :-
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# Load dataset
df = sns.load_dataset("titanic")
print("----- DATA PREVIEW -----")
print(df.head())
print("\n----- DATA INFO -----")
print(df.info())
# Count plot (Survival)
sns.countplot(x="survived", data=df)
plt.title("Survival Count")
plt.show()
# Count plot (Gender vs Survival)
sns.countplot(x="sex", hue="survived", data=df)
plt.title("Survival based on Gender")
plt.show()
# Count plot (Class vs Survival)
sns.countplot(x="pclass", hue="survived", data=df)
plt.title("Survival based on Passenger Class")
plt.show()
# Histogram of fare
sns.histplot(df["fare"], bins=30, kde=True)
plt.title("Fare Distribution")
plt.xlabel("Fare")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.show()

########Explanation 

import seaborn as sns
Imports the Seaborn library.
sns is a short name (alias) for seaborn.
Seaborn is used for data visualization.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
Imports pyplot module from Matplotlib library.
plt is an alias.

Used to display graphs and charts.
# Load dataset
This is a comment.

Used to explain the code.

df = sns.load_dataset("titanic")
Loads the built-in Titanic dataset from Seaborn.
Stores it in variable df.
df means DataFrame (table format data).

print("----- DATA PREVIEW -----")
Prints the heading DATA PREVIEW.

print(df.head())
Displays the first 5 rows of the dataset.

Used to quickly check data.

print("\n----- DATA INFO -----")
Prints a new heading.

\n means new line.

print(df.info())
Shows information about dataset:
Number of rows and columns
Data types
Missing values

Count Plot – Survival
sns.countplot(x="survived", data=df)
Creates a count plot.
Counts how many passengers:
Survived (1)
Did not survive (0)

x="survived" → variable shown on x-axis.

data=df → dataset used.

plt.title("Survival Count")
Adds title to graph.

plt.show()
Displays the graph.

Count Plot – Gender vs Survival
sns.countplot(x="sex", hue="survived", data=df)
Creates count plot for male and female passengers.
hue="survived" separates bars by survival status.
Helps compare survival based on gender.
plt.title("Survival based on Gender")
Adds graph title.

plt.show()
Displays graph.

Count Plot – Passenger Class vs Survival
sns.countplot(x="pclass", hue="survived", data=df)
Creates plot for passenger classes:
1 = First class

2 = Second class

3 = Third class

hue="survived" shows survival comparison.

plt.title("Survival based on Passenger Class")
Adds title.

plt.show()
Displays graph.

Histogram of Fare
sns.histplot(df["fare"], bins=30, kde=True)
Creates a histogram of ticket fare.

df["fare"] → fare column.

bins=30 → divides data into 30 groups.

kde=True → draws smooth density curve.

plt.title("Fare Distribution")
Adds title to histogram.

plt.xlabel("Fare")
Labels x-axis as Fare.

plt.ylabel("Count")
Labels y-axis as Count.

plt.show()
Displays histogram.

